Part 3

Ramanna asked him on the fifth morning, formally, standing straighter than Vikram had yet seen him stand.

"Sir. My daughter's marriage. Day after tomorrow. You are staying at my house. It would be my honour if you attend."

"I don't want to intrude on—"

"Intrude?" Ramanna looked genuinely wounded by the word. "You are staying under my roof. If you don't come, the whole village will ask what is wrong with my hospitality."

Vikram went.

---

The wedding took over the entire lane outside Ramanna's house — a pandal of bamboo and cloth thrown up in two days, banana stems tied to every pillar, mango leaves strung across the entrance in lines that dipped and rose like something breathing.

Somebody put a plate in his hands before he'd finished taking off his shoes.

"Eat, eat," said a woman he hadn't been introduced to, ladling a second helping of sambar onto his banana leaf before he could protest that he hadn't finished the first. "You've come from so far. You'll eat properly in this house."

He tried explaining he was only staying two days.

She didn't appear to hear that part.

---

By the second course he'd been fed by at least four different aunts, each one convinced the previous three hadn't fed him enough, and been informed by an uncle with a paan-stained smile that he looked "too thin for a business man, no offense," which Vikram found he didn't take as one.

The wedding itself happened in pieces he only half followed — the priest's Sanskrit running fast and rhythmic over the fire, Lakshmi in temple jewellery that looked too heavy for her thin wrists, her new husband's hands shaking slightly during the mangalsutra, a roar of conch shells and ululation that made Vikram's ears ring pleasantly for a full minute after.

Nobody asked him for anything.

Nobody wanted a licence signed, a policy explained, a board satisfied.

They wanted him to eat more, which he found, to his own surprise, he didn't mind at all.

---

On the second evening, sitting on Ramanna's veranda with his phone against his ear, he could hear the wedding band still going somewhere behind him.

"Sir, the minister's office confirmed Thursday," his assistant said. "Reddy sir will meet you there directly."

"Good."

"Also, sir — are you well? You sound different."

Vikram considered several ways of answering that were true.

"I've been eating a lot of sambar," he said finally.

His assistant, after a pause, decided not to ask further, which Vikram appreciated more than she probably knew.

---

Ramanna found him there after the call ended, two cups of over-sweet tea in hand, and settled onto the step without waiting to be invited, the way only a man who has decided you now belong a little to his house would.

"Good wedding?" Vikram asked.

"Good wedding," Ramanna agreed, then, after a moment, added the only compliment he seemed to consider worth giving. "You ate properly, at least. My wife was worried a big company man wouldn't eat village food."

"It was better than anything the company canteen serves."

Ramanna laughed — a short, surprised bark of a laugh, as if he hadn't expected to be believed.

They sat a while, saying nothing further, the band behind them working through the same four songs for the third time that night, neither man minding it in the least.
